## 1. Phase One Objectives

Phase One has four primary goals:

1. **Validate electrostatic loft efficiency** in vacuum using lunar regolith simulant.  
2. **Quantify micro-collision erosion** caused by terrace geometry (grain “softening”).  
3. **Assess long-duration survivability** of terraces and dielectric layers under realistic stress.  
4. **Establish validated models** (DEM, electrostatic, thermal) to project multi-year behavior.

Secondary goals:

- Characterize **HV cycling fatigue** of the dielectric stack.  
- Validate **power budget realism** vs. Phase Zero estimates.  
- Confirm **electronics coffin thermal stability** under extreme temperature swings.

At the end of Phase One, the LDM must either:

- **Advance** to Phase Two engineering model development,  
- **Advance conditionally** with specific redesigns, or  
- Be **terminated or heavily re-scoped** if core physics or survivability claims fail.

---

## 2. Experimental Campaign Design

Phase One runs four major experiments plus piggyback measurements.

### 2.1 Experiment A — Vacuum Electrostatic Loft Test

**Purpose:**  
Prove that a fixed-bias plate under a dielectric can loft fine-grain simulant under lunar-like vacuum. (Target A)

**Test Articles:**

- Plate Stack A1 (HV plate + dielectric + ground plane)  
- Regolith simulant batches (e.g., JSC-1A-like, fine fraction `< 75 µm`)

**Apparatus & Conditions:**

- Vacuum chamber: 10⁻⁵–10⁻⁶ torr  
- HV supply: adjustable, current-limited, up to tens of kV (as needed)  
- Imaging: side-view camera with backlighting if possible

**Measured Quantities:**

- Loft height vs. applied voltage  
- Loft onset threshold  
- Loft repeatability over N cycles  
- Energy per loft cycle (V · I · t)

**Run Plan:**

- Sweep 5–7 voltage levels  
- ≥5 runs per level  
- Log voltage, current, pressure, timestamps

---

### 2.2 Experiment B — Micro-Collision Erosion Test

**Purpose:**  
Show that repeated low-energy collisions on terrace geometry measurably blunt grains. (Target B)

**Test Articles:**

- Terrace coupons (same geometry as LDM terraces)  
- Simulant batches pre-characterized for angularity

**Apparatus & Conditions:**

- Gravity drop/slide rig  
- Optional mild vibration to simulate micro-disturbances

**Measured Quantities:**

- Angularity distributions **before** and **after** testing  
- Estimated collisions per grain  
- Evolution of the extreme angular tail

**Run Plan:**

- At least 3 collision exposure levels (e.g., 10³, 10⁴, 10⁵ equivalent passes)  
- SEM/micro-CT or equivalent imaging for each level

---

### 2.3 Experiment C — Terrace Saturation & Flow Behavior

**Purpose:**  
Evaluate whether terraces clog, self-level, or self-clear under sustained dust loading. (Target C)

**Test Articles:**

- Larger terrace module (~20–50 cm active area)

**Apparatus & Conditions:**

- Dust feeder system (slow drip/sprinkle onto terraces)  
- Optional vibration source

**Measured Quantities:**

- Dust height profile along terraces vs. time  
- Time to saturation/clogging  
- Conditions under which terraces clear or self-level  
- Terrace wear / geometry change

**Run Plan:**

- Accelerated “months–years” of dust events  
- Periodic imaging/profiling  
- Test multiple geometries (baseline + variant)

---

### 2.4 Experiment D — Thermal & Dielectric Endurance

**Purpose:**  
Verify dielectric stack and coatings survive lunar-style thermal swings and HV cycling. (Targets D/E)

**Test Articles:**

- Dielectric-coated plates and stack coupons  
- Potted PCB blocks representing electronics coffin materials

**Apparatus & Conditions:**

- Thermal chamber: approx. −150 °C to +120 °C  
- Cycle count (Phase One):  
  - Coupons: ≥100 cycles  
  - EDU: 20–50 cycles (system-level check)  
- Optional parallel HV cycling at selected intervals

**Measured Quantities:**

- Visual/mechanical damage (cracks, delamination)  
- Dielectric breakdown voltage pre/post  
- Leakage current trend  
- Coffin potting integrity

---

### 2.5 Supporting Piggyback Measurements

- **HV cycling fatigue** (dielectric endurance vs. pulses)  
- **Power budget reality check** (measured vs. modeled energy per event)  
- **Electronics coffin thermal behavior** (internal vs. external temperatures)

---

### 2.6 Experimental Campaign Summary Table

| Experiment | Goal                                      | Primary Outputs                                  |
|-----------|-------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| A         | Prove electrostatic loft in vacuum        | Loft height vs. voltage; onset; power cost       |
| B         | Prove micro-collision grain softening     | Angularity histograms; change vs. cycles         |
| C         | Characterize terrace saturation/flow      | Terrace fill curves; clog vs. clear conditions   |
| D         | Validate thermal & dielectric endurance   | Breakdown vs. cycles; failure thresholds         |
| E (piggyback) | HV cycling fatigue                    | HV endurance curves                              |
| F (piggyback) | Power budget validation               | Measured vs. modeled power consumption           |
| G (piggyback) | Coffin thermal stability              | Internal vs. external temperature curves         |

---

## 3. Prototype Definitions & Build Specs

Three main prototypes support the Phase One work.

### 3.1 Prototype A — Electrostatic Plate Testbed

**Role:**  
Primary hardware for Experiment A (loft) and part of Experiment D (dielectric endurance).

**Geometry:**

- Plate: circular, Ø ≈ 150–200 mm (6–8")  
- Stack: HV plate + dielectric top + ground reference plane  
- HV–ground gap: ~5–20 mm (for manageable HV)

**Materials Stack-Up:**

- HV Plate: Al 6061, ~3–5 mm thick  
- Dielectric: Kapton or thin ceramic/glass-ceramic, ~50–500 μm  
- Ground Plane: Al or Cu, tied to chamber ground

**Interfaces:**

- HV connection with strain relief and shielding  
- Ground bonded to chamber  
- Optional series resistor for safety  
- Mounting holes or clamps for chamber fixture

---

### 3.2 Prototype B — Terrace Agitation Module

**Role:**  
Primary hardware for Experiment B (grain softening) and Experiment C (terrace behavior).

**Geometry:**

- Footprint: ~300 × 300 mm active region  
- Terrace geometry (baseline):  
  - Step height: 2–10 mm  
  - Step run: 10–30 mm  
  - Effective slope: ~10–30°  
- Channels can be straight (baseline) and optionally curved (variant).

**Materials:**

- Base: Al 6061 / stainless / machinable ceramic  
- Surface finish: moderate roughness; avoid deep grooves  
- Optional coatings: hard anodize or ceramic; at least one uncoated baseline.

**Variants:**

- B1: Baseline geometry  
- B2: Alternate geometry (different step height/slope)

---

### 3.3 Prototype C — Integrated EDU (Engineering Development Unit)

**Role:**  
First full-body LDM mock-up (non-flight). Used for integration checks, power testing, and partial thermal validation.

**Overall Geometry:**

- Chassis: ~400–600 mm (L) × 300–400 mm (W) × 200–300 mm (H)  
- Visual form: boxy, Crawler-derived, no delicate appendages

**Subsystem Placement:**

- Top: solar region + terrace region  
- Internal: sealed electronics coffin near thermal/structural center  
- Bottom: flat contact surfaces + structural ribs

**Materials & Construction:**

- Chassis: metal shell, 2–5 mm thick  
- Coffin: sealed metal box, fully potted PCB  
- Terraces: integrated or removable module matching Prototype B

**Electrical Architecture:**

- Power:  
  - Option A: Small real solar + battery  
  - Option B: Bench supply emulating solar+battery (lab mode)  

- Control:  
  - Simple timer/MCU controlling HV duty cycle  

- HV Path:  
  - PCB → HV module → feedthrough → plate array under terraces

**Thermal Features:**

- Conductive paths from coffin to chassis  
- Radiator surfaces (fins/panels) on exterior  
- No pumps or active cooling

---

### 3.4 Build Priorities & Non-Goals

**Priorities:**

- Prototype A: clean HV behavior in vacuum, safe and well-instrumented  
- Prototype B: geometrically faithful terraces, robust for abrasion  
- Prototype C: realistic integration to expose architectural problems

**Non-Goals for Phase One:**

- No space-rated electronics or harness  
- No full flight-level structural qualification  
- No complex telemetry or sensor suites  
- No multi-unit swarm or network behaviors

---

## 4. Modeling & Simulation Plan

Phase One modeling supports, not replaces, experiments.

### 4.1 DEM — Dust Collision & Grain Softening

**Purpose:**  
Quantify grain-shape evolution under terrace collisions and scale lab results to mission timescales.

**Inputs:**

- Grain size distribution from simulant  
- Material properties (density, friction, hardness approx.)  
- Terrace geometry from Prototype B CAD  
- Initial angularity distribution from SEM/micro-CT  

**Outputs:**

- Collisions per grain vs. time  
- Impact energy distributions  
- “Sharpness” metric evolution vs. cycles  
- Predicted % change in angular tail

**Validation:**

- Compare DEM results to Experiment B data  
- Accept factor-of-two agreement; adjust only within physically justified bounds

---

### 4.2 Electrostatic Field Modeling

**Purpose:**  
Predict field distribution, loft onset voltages, and dielectric breakdown margins.

**Inputs:**

- Prototype A geometry  
- Dielectric thickness / permittivity  
- Voltage sweep across test range  
- Approximate dust surface behavior if needed

**Outputs:**

- Field strength at surface vs. applied voltage  
- Approximate lift threshold vs. grain charge/mass  
- Peak field inside dielectric vs. breakdown strength

**Validation:**

- Compare predicted loft onset vs. Experiment A  
- Compare predicted breakdown margins vs. Experiment D failures (if any)

---

### 4.3 Thermal Modeling (FEA)

**Purpose:**  
Ensure electronics coffin and chassis stay within survivable temperatures.

**Inputs:**

- EDU geometry (Prototype C)  
- Material thermal properties  
- Boundary conditions: solar load, view to space, regolith contact model  
- Internal heat load from electronics

**Outputs:**

- Temperature vs. time at coffin interior/exterior  
- Chassis/radiator temperature profiles  
- Diurnal swing amplitudes

**Validation:**

- Compare to chamber tests (EDU and coffin coupons)  
- Accept ±15 °C tolerance, refine contact/emissivity parameters accordingly

---

### 4.4 Model Integration

Combined use:

- DEM + electrostatics → cycles/day and collisions/grain over mission duration.  
- Thermal model → realistic duty cycle constraints for HV events.

Models must be explicitly documented and archived for independent review.

---

## 5. Environmental Testing Matrix & Schedules

### 5.1 Prototype-Level Test Matrix

**Prototype A — Plate Testbed**

- Vacuum loft: **Required**  
- HV cycling fatigue: **Required**  
- Thermal cycling: Coupon-level **required**; full plate as needed  

**Prototype B — Terrace Module**

- Abrasion / dust: **Required**  
- Vacuum: **Optional** (benchtop acceptable)  
- Vibration: **Optional** for flow behavior  

**Prototype C — EDU**

- Thermal cycling: **Required**  
- Power cycle tests: **Required**  
- Limited vacuum: **Strongly recommended**  
- Vibration: **Optional** (Phase Two focus)

---

### 5.2 Test Conditions

- Thermal range: approx. −150 °C to +120 °C  
- Coupon cycles: ≥100  
- EDU cycles: 20–50 minimum  
- Vacuum: 10⁻⁵–10⁻⁶ torr for loft tests

HV duty-cycle acceleration:  
- Compress years of operation into **1,000–10,000** HV events for fatigue characterization.

---

### 5.3 Sequencing & Parallelization

Logical order:

1. Material coupons (thermal/dielectric)  
2. Prototype A loft tests  
3. Prototype B collision/abrasion tests  
4. Prototype A HV endurance tests  
5. Prototype C EDU build + thermal/power tests  
6. Optional integration vacuum checks

Parallelization for a 12-month SBIR-scale effort:

- Months 0–2: Coupons + first-pass designs  
- Months 2–4: Prototype A & B main experiments  
- Months 4–6: Extended abrasion + HV fatigue; start EDU build  
- Months 6–9: EDU thermal and power tests; model refinement  
- Months 9–12: Re-tests, final alignment, reporting

---

## 6. Success Criteria & Go/No-Go Gates

### 6.1 Physics-Level Criteria

**Loft Success:**

- Fine simulant (≤50–100 μm) lofts in vacuum at ≤10⁻⁵ torr  
- Onset voltage within ±30% of model predictions  
- Repeatable across ≥3 independent runs  

**Grain Softening Success:**

- ≥1–5% reduction in extreme angular tail after accelerated cycles  
- Trend matches DEM direction and order of magnitude  

---

### 6.2 Materials-Level Criteria

**Dielectric Integrity:**

- ≥1,000–10,000 HV cycles without catastrophic breakdown  
- Leakage current within modeled expectations

**Terrace Durability:**

- ≤5% loss of critical dimensions after long-duration abrasion tests  
- Terraces remain functionally shaped

---

### 6.3 System-Level Criteria

**Coffin Thermal Survivability:**

- Coffin interior remains within:  
  - Tmax ≤ 120 °C  
  - Tmin ≥ −50 °C (or per chosen parts)  
- Thermal model matches data within ±15 °C

**Power Feasibility:**

- HV event energy cost within ±25% of model  
- Duty cycle sustainable with plausible small-solar/battery architecture

**Integration Stability:**

- No HV runaway  
- No severe cross-talk or uncontrolled EMI  
- No structural damage due to thermal cycles

---

### 6.4 Model–Experiment Agreement

**DEM:**  
- Angularity evolution and collision statistics match experiments within factor-of-two.

**Electrostatic:**  
- Loft onset and breakdown margin predictions match measured behavior within stated tolerances.

**Thermal:**  
- Coffin and chassis temperature curves agree within ±15 °C of chamber data.

---

### 6.5 Go/No-Go Decision Outcomes

**GO:**  
- Loft works, softening is real, terraces viable, dielectric/thermal margins are acceptable, and models align with experiments.  
- Recommendation: advance to Phase Two engineering model.

**CONDITIONAL GO:**  
- Core physics work, but redesign needed (materials, terrace geometry, duty cycle, coffin design).  
- Recommendation: advance with explicit redesign items.

**NO-GO:**  
- Loft unobtainable at realistic voltages, no grain softening, catastrophic material/thermal issues, or models irreconcilable with data.  
- Recommendation: terminate or pivot; LDM not worth further funding in current form.

---

## 7. Final Deliverables & Reporting Requirements

### 7.1 Written Technical Deliverables

**Phase One Final Report:**

- Executive summary  
- System overview  
- Phase Zero recap  
- Phase One methodology  
- Experimental results (A–D)  
- Model–experiment alignment  
- Conclusions & Go/No-Go recommendation  
- Appendices with raw data, CAD, ACS2, material certs, test logs

**Standalone Modeling Packages:**

- DEM package  
- Electrostatic package  
- Thermal package  

Each with assumptions, inputs, outputs, comparison plots, and caveats.

**Operational Test Logs:**

- Loft, HV, abrasion, thermal, EDU power-cycle logs  
- Anomaly reports  
- Configuration and versioning information

---

### 7.2 Hardware Deliverables

- Prototype A documentation (and hardware if required)  
- Prototype B documentation (and hardware if required)  
- Prototype C EDU documentation (as-built, photos, PCB layouts, routing diagrams)

Physical transfer of hardware depends on NASA/contract terms; documentation is always required.

---

### 7.3 Data Deliverables

- Raw experimental data in CSV/TXT form  
- Video/time-lapse evidence of key tests  
- Material and component specifications and certs

---

### 7.4 Review Board Package

- Slide deck summarizing all results  
- Plots of key figures of merit  
- Comparison of predicted vs. measured performance  
- Clear Go/Conditional Go/No-Go recommendation  
- Phase Two concept outline and cost/schedule sketch

---

### 7.5 Reporting Timeline

- **Mid-Term Report (~3–4 months):**  
  - Early results  
  - Emerging risks or deviations  
  - Any test matrix changes

- **Final Report (~12 months):**  
  - Full dataset  
  - Final models  
  - Final decision recommendation

---

### 7.6 Archival Requirements

- CAD in neutral formats (STEP/IGES)  
- Models, scripts, and configs archived (e.g., in this repo or linked)  
- Test logs timestamped and version-controlled  
- ACS2 diagrams stored as text and PDF

---

## Summary

Phase One is designed to be:

- technically honest,  
- experimentally grounded,  
- and realistically executable within a 6–12 month SBIR-style effort.

If successful, it will:

- prove LDM’s physics,  
- validate its survivability,  
- and produce a defensible basis for a Phase Two engineering model and eventual lunar demo as a passive dust-conditioning asset for surface infrastructure.

